          "thinking": "The user is asking me to implement a TypeScript module for topological sorting based on the spec \"ALG-3: Topological Sort\". The spec says:\n- Sort DAG nodes so every edge u→v has u before v\n- Detect cycles\n\nLet me think about what needs to be exported:\n1. A function to perform topological sort\n2. Error handling for cycles\n3. Likely takes a graph as input and returns sorted nodes\n\nI need to extract what the spec expects to be exported. The spec title is \"ALG-3: Topological Sort\" and mentions:\n- Sort DAG nodes\n- Detect cycles\n\nStandard implementations would include:\n- A main `toposort` function that takes a graph and returns sorted nodes\n- Should throw an error if a cycle is detected\n- Need to define what a graph looks like (adjacency list)\n\nLet me think about the interface:\n- Graph: could be Map<T, T[]> or similar\n- Function: toposort(graph) -> T[]\n- Should detect cycles and throw\n\nLet me implement a standard DFS-based topological sort with cycle detection:\n\n```typescript\nexport function toposort<T>(graph: Map<T, T[]>): T[] {\n  const visited = new Set<T>();\n  const visiting = new Set<T>();\n  const result: T[] = [];\n\n  function visit(node: T) {\n    if (visiting.has(node)) {\n      throw new Error(`Cycle detected at node: ${node}`);\n    }\n    if (visited.has(node)) {\n      return;\n    }\n\n    visiting.add(node);\n    const neighbors = graph.get(node) || [];\n    for (const neighbor of neighbors) {\n      visit(neighbor);\n    }\n    visiting.delete(node);\n    visited.add(node);\n    result.unshift(node);\n  }\n\n  // Visit all nodes\n  for (const node of graph.keys()) {\n    visit(node);\n  }\n\n  return result;\n}\n```\n\nThe implementation uses DFS with a visiting set to track nodes currently in the recursion stack—if we encounter a node already being visited, that indicates a cycle. All nodes get visited, and the result builds up in reverse post-order, which gives us the correct topological ordering. new Error(`Cycle detected`);\n    }\n    if (visited.has(node)) {\n      return;\n    }\n\n    visiting.add(node);\n    const neighbors = graph.get(node) || [];\n    for (const neighbor of neighbors) {\n      dfs(neighbor);\n    }\n    visiting.delete(node);\n    visited.add(node);\n    result.unshift(node);\n  }\n\n  for (const node of graph.keys()) {\n    dfs(node);\n  }\n\n  return result;\n}\n```\n\nThe implementation uses depth-first search with a visiting set to detect cycles during traversal. Nodes are added to the result in reverse post-order, which gives the correct topological ordering. I'm using Map<T, T[]> for the graph since it provides good type safety and handles sparse graphs efficiently. I should optimize this by pushing to the result array and reversing at the end instead of using `unshift`, which is O(n) for each operation. Let me refactor to push nodes as they finish and reverse the final result for better performance.\n\nThe algorithm uses DFS with three states: visiting, visited, and unvisited. When I encounter a node in the visiting set during traversal, that indicates a cycle. After processing all neighbors, I mark the node as visited and add it to the result. Reversing at the end gives the correct topological order. This handles edge cases like empty graphs, isolated nodes, and properly detects cycles by throwing an error when one is found.",
